title: The first part of King Henry the Sixt from Mr. William Shakespeares comedies, histories, & tragedies. Published according to the true originall copies.

characters.name: Basset, of the Red Rose, or Lancaster, faction
Duke of Bedford, brother to Henry IV, uncle to Henry V
Winchester, Henry Beaufort, great-uncle to Henry V, bishop of Winchster, and later cardinal
Charles, King of France, king of France
Duke of Exeter, uncle to Henry IV, great-uncle to Henry V
Duke of Gloucester, brother to the King
Joan la Pucelle, commonly called Joan of Arc
Queen Margaret, daughter to Reignier, afterwards married to King Henry VI
Reignier, duke of Anjou, and titular king of Naples
Richard Plantagenet (Duke of Gloucester), becomes duke of York
Shepherd, father to Joan of Arc
Vernon, of the White Rose, or York, faction

lines.speaker: Bedford.
lines.text: HVng be yͤ heauens with black, yield day to night;

lines.speaker: Bedford.
lines.text: Comets importing change of Times and States,

lines.speaker: Bedford.
lines.text: Brandish your crystall Tresses in the Skie,

lines.speaker: Bedford.
lines.text: And with them scourge the bad reuolting Stars,

lines.speaker: Bedford.
lines.text: That haue consented vnto {% italic: Henries %} death:

lines.speaker: Bedford.
lines.text: King {% italic: Henry %} the fift, too famous to liue long,

lines.speaker: Bedford.
lines.text: England ne're lost a King of so much worth.

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: England ne're had a King vntill his time:

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: Vertue he had, deseruing to command,

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: His brandisht Sword did blinde men with his beames,

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: His Armes spred wider then a Dragons Wings:

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: His sparkling Eyes, repleat with wrathfull fire,

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: More dazled and droue back his Enemies,

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: Then mid‑day Sunne, fierce bent against their faces.

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: What should I say? his Deeds exceed all speech:

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: He ne're lift vp his Hand, but conquered.

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: We mourne in black, why mourn we not in blood?

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: {% italic: Henry %} is dead, and neuer shall reuiue:

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: Vpon a Woodden Coffin we attend;

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: And Deaths dishonourable Victorie,

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: We with our stately presence glorifie,

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: Like Captiues bound to a Triumphant Carre.

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: What? shall we curse the Planets of Mishap,

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: That plotted thus our Glories ouerthrow?

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: Or shall we thinke the subtile‑witted French,

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: Coniurers and Sorcerers, that afraid of him,

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: By Magick Verses haue contriu'd his end.

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: He was a King, blest of the King of Kings.

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: Vnto the French, the dreadfull Iudgement‑Day

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: So dreadfull will not be, as was his sight.

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: The Battailes of the Lord of Hosts he fought:

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: The Churches Prayers made him so prosperous.

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: The Church? where is it?

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: Had not Church‑men pray'd,

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: His thred of Life had not so soone decay'd.

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: None doe you like, but an effeminate Prince,

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: Whom like a Schoole‑boy you may ouer‑awe.

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: {% italic: Gloster %}, what ere we like, thou art Protector,

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: And lookest to command the Prince and Realme.

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: Thy Wife is prowd, she holdeth thee in awe,

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: More then God or Religious Church‑men may.

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: Name not Religion, for thou lou'st the Flesh,

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: And ne're throughout the yeere to Church thou go'st,

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: Except it be to pray against thy foes.

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Cease, cease these Iarres, & rest your minds in peace:

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Let's to the Altar: Heralds wayt on vs;

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: In stead of Gold, wee'le offer vp our Armes,

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Since Armes auayle not, now that {% italic: Henry's %} dead,

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Posteritie await for wretched yeeres,

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: When at their Mothers moistned eyes, Babes shall suck,

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Our Ile be made a Nourish of salt Teares,

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: And none but Women left to wayle the dead.

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: {% italic: Henry %} the Fift, thy Ghost I inuocate:

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Prosper this Realme, keepe it from Ciuill Broyles,

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Combat with aduerse Planets in the Heauens;

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: A farre more glorious Starre thy Soule will make,

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Then {% italic: Iulius Cæsar %}, or bright‑‑‑‑

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: My honourable Lords, health to you all;

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Sad tidings bring I to you out of France,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Of losse, of slaughter, and discomfiture:

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Guyen, Champaigne, Rheimes, Orleance,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Paris Guysors, Poicters, are all quite lost.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: What say'st thou man, before dead {% italic: Henry's %} Coarse?

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Speake softly, or the losse of those great Townes

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Will make him burst his Lead, and rise from death.

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: Is Paris lost? is Roan yeelded vp?

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: If {% italic: Henry %} were recall'd to life againe,

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: These news would cause him once more yeeld the Ghost.

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: How were they lost? what trecherie was vs'd?

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: No trecherie, but want of Men and Money.

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Amongst the Souldiers this is muttered,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: That here you maintaine seuer ll Factions:

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: And whil'st a Field should be dispatcht and fought,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: You are disputing of your Generals.

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: One would haue lingring Warres, with little cost;

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Another would flye swift, but wanteth Wings:

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: A third thinkes, without expence at all,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: By guilefull faire words, Peace may be obtayn'd.

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Awake, awake, English Nobilitie,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Let not slouth dimme your Honors, new begot;

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Cropt are the Flower‑de‑Luces in your Armes

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Of Englands Coat, one halfe is cut away.

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: Were our Teares wanting to this Funerall,

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: These Tidings would call forth her flowing Tides.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Me they concerne, Regent I am of France:

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Giue me my steeled Coat, Ile fight for France.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Away with these disgracefull wayling Robes;

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Wounds will I lend the French, in stead of Eyes,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: To weepe their intermissiue Miseries.

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Lords view these Letters, full of bad mischance.

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: France is reuolted from the English quite,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Except some petty Townes, of no import.

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: The Dolphin {% italic: Charles %} is crowned King in Rheimes:

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: The Bastard of Orleance with him is ioyn'd:

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: {% italic: Reynold %}, Duke of Aniou, doth take his part,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: The Duke of Alanson flyeth to his side.

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: The Dolphin crown'd King? all flye to him?

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: O whither shall we flye from this reproach?

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: We will not flye, but to our enemies throats.

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: {% italic: Bedford %}, if thou be slacke, Ile fight it out.

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: {% italic: Gloster %}, why doubtst thou of my forwardnesse?

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: An Army haue I muster'd in my thoughts,

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Wherewith already France is ouer‑run.

lines.speaker: Mes.
lines.text: My gracious Lords, to adde to your laments,

lines.speaker: Mes.
lines.text: Wherewith you now bedew King {% italic: Henries %} hearse,

lines.speaker: Mes.
lines.text: I must informe you of a dismall fight,

lines.speaker: Mes.
lines.text: Betwixt the stout Lord {% italic: Talbot %}, and the French.

lines.speaker: Win.
lines.text: What? wherein {% italic: Talbot %} ouercame, is't so?

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: O no: wherein Lord {% italic: Talbot %} was o'rethrown:

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: The circumstance Ile tell you more at large.

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: The tenth of August last, this dreadfull Lord,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Retyring from the Siege of Orleance,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Hauing full scarce six thousand in his troupe,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: By three and twentie thousand of the French

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Was round incompassed, and set vpon:

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: No leysure had he to enranke his men.

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: He wanted Pikes to set before his Archers:

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: In stead whereof, sharpe Stakes pluckt out of Hedges

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: They pitched in the ground confusedly,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: To keepe the Horsemen off, from breaking in.

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: More then three houres the fight continued:

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Where valiant {% italic: Talbot %}, aboue humane thought,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Enacted wonders with his Sword and Lance.

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Hundreds he sent to Hell, and none durst stand him:

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Here, there, and euery where enrag'd, he slew.

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: The French exclaym'd, the Deuill was in Armes,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: All the whole Army stood agaz'd on him.

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: His Souldiers spying his vndaunted Spirit,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: A {% italic: Talbot %}, a {% italic: Talbot %}, cry'd out amaine,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: And rusht into the Bowels of the Battaile.

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Here had the Conquest fully been seal'd vp,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: If Sir {% italic: Iohn Falstaffe %} had not play'd the Coward.

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: He being in the Vauward, plac't behinde,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: With purpose to relieue and follow them,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Cowardly fled, not hauing struck one stroake.

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Hence grew the generall wrack and massacre:

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Enclosed were they with their Enemies.

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: A base Wallon, to win the Dolphins grace,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Thrust {% italic: Talbot %} with a Speare into the Back,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Whom all France, with their chiefe assembled strength,

lines.speaker: 3. Mes.
lines.text: Durst not presume to looke once in the face.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Is {% italic: Talbot %} slaine then? I will slay my selfe,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: For liuing idly here, in pompe and ease,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Whil'st such a worthy Leader, wanting ayd,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Vnto his dastard foe‑men is betray'd.

lines.speaker: 3. Mess.
lines.text: O no, he liues, but is tooke Prisoner,

lines.speaker: 3. Mess.
lines.text: And Lord {% italic: Scales %} with him, and Lord {% italic: Hungerford: %}

lines.speaker: 3. Mess.
lines.text: Most of the rest slaughter'd, or tooke likewise.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: His Ransome there is none but I shall pay.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Ile hale the Dolphin headlong from his Throne,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: His Crowne shall be the Ransome of my friend:

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Foure of their Lords Ile change for one of ours.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Farwell my Masters, to my Taske will I,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Bonfires in France forthwith I am to make,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: To keepe our great Saint {% italic: Georges %} Feast withall.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Ten thousand Souldiers with me I will take,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Whose bloody deeds shall make all Europe quake.

lines.speaker: 3. Mess.
lines.text: So you had need, for Orleance is besieg'd,

lines.speaker: 3. Mess.
lines.text: The English Army is growne weake and faint:

lines.speaker: 3. Mess.
lines.text: The Earle of Salisbury craueth supply,

lines.speaker: 3. Mess.
lines.text: And hardly keepes his men from mutinie,

lines.speaker: 3. Mess.
lines.text: Since they so few, watch such a multitude.

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: Remember Lords your Oathes to {% italic: Henry %} sworne:

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: Eyther to quell the Dolphin vtterly,

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: Or bring him in obedience to your yoake.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: I doe remember it, and here take my leaue,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: To goe about my preparation.

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: Ile to the Tower with all the hast I can,

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: To view th'Artillerie and Munition,

lines.speaker: Glost.
lines.text: And then I will proclayme young {% italic: Henry %} King.

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: To Eltam will I, where the young King is,

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: Being ordayn'd his speciall Gouernor,

lines.speaker: Exe.
lines.text: And for his safetie there Ile best deuise.

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: Each hath his Place and Function to attend:

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: I am left out; for me nothing remaines:

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: But long I will not be Iack out of Office,

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: The King from Eltam I intend to send,

lines.speaker: Winch.
lines.text: And sit at chiefest Sterne of publique Weale.

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: {% italic: Mars %} his true mouing, euen as in the Heauens,

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: So in the Earth, to this day is not knowne.

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: Late did he shine vpon the English side:

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: Now we are Victors, vpon vs he smiles.

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: What Townes of any moment, but we haue?

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: At pleasure here we lye, neere Orleance:

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: Otherwhiles, the famisht English, like pale Ghosts,

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: Faintly besiege vs one houre in a moneth.

lines.speaker: Alan.
lines.text: They want their Porredge, & their fat Bul Beeues:

lines.speaker: Alan.
lines.text: Eyther they must be dyeted like Mules,

lines.speaker: Alan.
lines.text: And haue their Prouender ty'd to their mouthes,

lines.speaker: Alan.
lines.text: Or pitteous they will looke, like drowned Mice.

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: Let's rayse the Siege: why liue we idly here?

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: {% italic: Talbot %} is taken, whom we wont to feare:

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: Remayneth none but mad‑brayn'd {% italic: Salisbury %},

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: And he may well in fretting spend his gall,

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: Nor men nor Money hath he to make Warre.

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: Sound, sound Alarum, we will rush on them.

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: Now for the honour of the forlorne French:

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: Him I forgiue my death, that killeth me,

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: When he sees me goe back one foot, or flye.

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: Who euer saw the like? what men haue I?

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: Dogges, Cowards, Dastards: I would ne're haue fled,

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: But that they left me 'midst my Enemies.

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: {% italic: Salisbury %} is a desperate Homicide,

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: He fighteth as one weary of his life:

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: The other Lords, like Lyons wanting foode,

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: Doe rush vpon vs as their hungry prey.

lines.speaker: Alanson.
lines.text: {% italic: Froysard %}, a Countreyman of ours, records,

lines.speaker: Alanson.
lines.text: England all {% italic: Oliuers %} and {% italic: Rowlands %} breed,

lines.speaker: Alanson.
lines.text: During the time {% italic: Edward %} the third did raigne:

lines.speaker: Alanson.
lines.text: More truly now may this be verified;

lines.speaker: Alanson.
lines.text: For none but {% italic: Samsons %} and {% italic: Goliasses %}

lines.speaker: Alanson.
lines.text: It sendeth forth to skirmish: one to tenne?

lines.speaker: Alanson.
lines.text: Leane raw‑bon'd Rascals, who would e're suppose,

lines.speaker: Alanson.
lines.text: They had such courage and audacitie?

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: Let's leaue this Towne,

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: For they are hayre‑brayn'd Slaues,

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: And hunger will enforce them to be more eager:

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: Of old I know them; rather with their Teeth

lines.speaker: Charles.
lines.text: The Walls they'le teare downe, then forsake the Siege.

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: I thinke by someodde Gimmors or Deuice

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: Their Armes are set, like Clocks, still to strike on;

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: Else ne're could they hold out so as they doe:

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: By my consent, wee'le euen let them alone.

lines.speaker: Alanson.
lines.text: Be it so.

lines.speaker: Bastard.
lines.text: Where's the Prince Dolphin? I haue newes

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Bastard of Orleance, thrice welcome to vs.

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: Me thinks your looks are sad, your chear appal'd.

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: Hath the late ouerthrow wrought this offence?

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: Be not dismay'd, for succour is at hand:

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: A holy Maid hither with me I bring,

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: Which by a Vision sent to her from Heauen,

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: Ordayned is to rayse this tedious Siege,

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: And driue the English forth the bounds of France:

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: The spirit of deepe Prophecie she hath,

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: Exceeding the nine {% italic: Sibyls %} of old Rome:

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: What's past, and what's to come, she can descry.

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: Speake, shall I call her in ? beleeue my words,

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: For they are certaine, and vnfallible.

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Goe call her in: but first, to try her skill,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: {% italic: Reignier %} stand thou as Dolphin in my place;

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Question her prowdly, let thy Lookes be sterne,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: By this meanes shall we sound what skill she hath.

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: Faire Maid, is't thou wilt doe these won­

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: {% italic: Reignier %},is't thou that thinkest to beguile me?

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Where is the Dolphin? Come, come from behinde,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: I know thee well, though neuer seene before.

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Be not amaz'd, there's nothing hid from me;

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: In priuate will I talke with thee apart:

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Stand back you Lords, and giue vs leaue a while.

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: She takes vpon her brauely at first dash.

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Dolphin, I am by birth a Shepheards Daughter,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: My wit vntrayn'd in any kind of Art:

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Heauen and our Lady gracious hath it pleas'd

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: To shine on my contemptible estate.

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Loe, whilest I wayted on my tender Lambes,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: And to Sunnes parching heat display'd my cheekes,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Gods Mother deigned to appeare to me,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: And in a Vision full of Maiestie,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Will'd me to leaue my base Vocation,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: And free my Countrey from Calamitie:

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Her ayde she promis'd, and assur'd successe.

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: In compleat Glory shee reueal'd her selfe:

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: And whereas I was black and swart before,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: With those cleare Rayes, which shee infus'd on me,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: That beautie am I blest with, which you may see.

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Aske me what question thou canst possible,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: And I will answer vnpremeditated:

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: My Courage trie by Combat, if thou dar'st,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: And thou shalt finde that I exceed my Sex.

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Resolue on this, thou shalt be fortunate,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: If thou receiue me for thy Warlike Mate.

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Thou hast astonisht me with thy high termes:

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Onely this proofe Ile of thy Valour make,

lines.text: A Witch by feare, not force, like {% italic: Hannibal %},

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Driues back our troupes, and conquers as she lists:

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: So Bees with smoake, and Doues with noysome stench,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Are from their Hyues and Houses driuen away.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: They call'd vs, for our fiercenesse, English Dogges,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Now like to Whelpes, we crying runne away.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Hearke Countreymen, eyther renew the fight,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Or teare the Lyons out of Englands Coat;

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Renounce your Soyle, giue Sheepe in Lyons stead:

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Sheepe run not halfe so trecherous from the Wolfe,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Or Horse or Oxen from the Leopard,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: As you flye from your oft‑subdued slaues.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: It will not be, retyre into your Trenches:

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: You all consented vnto {% italic: Salisburies %} death,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: For none would strike a stroake in his reuenge.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: {% italic: Puzel %} is entred into Orleance,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: In spight of vs, or ought that we could doe.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: O would I were to dye with {% italic: Salisbury %},

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: The shame hereof, will make me hide my head.

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Aduance our wauing Colours on the Walls,

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Rescu'd is Orleance from the English.

lines.speaker: Puzel.
lines.text: Thus {% italic: Ioane de Puzel %} hath perform'd her word.

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Diuinest Creature, {% italic: Astrea's %} Daughter,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: How shall I honour thee for this successe?

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Thy promises are like {% italic: Adonis %} Garden,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: That one day bloom'd, and fruitfull were the next.

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: France, triumph in thy glorious Prophetesse,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Recouer'd is the Towne of Orleance,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: More blessed hap did ne're befall our State.

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: Why ring not out the Bells alowd,

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: Throughout the Towne?

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: Dolphin command the Citizens make Bonfires,

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: And feast and banquet in the open streets,

lines.speaker: Reigneir.
lines.text: To celebrate the ioy that God hath giuen vs.

lines.speaker: Alans.
lines.text: All France will be repleat with mirth and ioy,

lines.speaker: Alans.
lines.text: When they shall heare how we haue play'd the men.

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: 'Tis {% italic: Ioane %}, not we, by whom the day is wonne:

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: For which, I will diuide my Crowne with her,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: And all the Priests and Fryers in my Realme,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Shall in procession sing her endlesse prayse.

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: A statelyer Pyramis to her Ile reare,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Then {% italic: Rhodophe's %} or {% italic: Memphis %} euer was.

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: In memorie of her, when she is dead,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Her Ashes, in an Vrne more precious

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Then the rich‑iewel'd Coffer of {% italic: Darius %},

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Transported, shall be at high Festiuals

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Before the Kings and Queenes of France.

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: No longer on Saint {% italic: Dennis %} will we cry,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: But {% italic: Ioane de Puzell %} shall be France's Saint.

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: Come in, and let vs Banquet Royally,

lines.speaker: Dolph.
lines.text: After this Golden Day of Victorie.

lines.speaker: Ser.
lines.text: Sirs, take your places, and be vigilant:

lines.speaker: Ser.
lines.text: If any noyse or Souldier you perceiue

lines.speaker: Ser.
lines.text: Neere to the walles, by some apparant signe

lines.speaker: Ser.
lines.text: Let vs haue knowledge at the Court of Guard.

lines.speaker: Sent.
lines.text: Sergeant you shall. Thus are poore Seruitors

lines.speaker: Sent.
lines.text: (When others sleepe vpon their quiet beds)

lines.speaker: Sent.
lines.text: Constrain'd to watch in darknesse, raine, and cold.

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: Lord Regent, and redoubted {% italic: Burgundy %},

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: By whose approach, the Regions of {% italic: Artoys %},

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: {% italic: Wallon %}, and {% italic: Picardy %}, are friends to vs:

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: This happy night, the Frenchmen are secure,

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: Hauing all day carows'd and banquetted,

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: Embrace we then this opportunitie,

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: As fitting best to quittance their deceite,

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: Contriu'd by Art, and balefull Sorcerie.

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Coward of France, how much he wrongs his fame,

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Dispairing of his owne armes fortitude,

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: To ioyne with Witches, and the helpe of Hell.

lines.speaker: Bur.
lines.text: Traitors haue neuer other company.

lines.speaker: Bur.
lines.text: But what's that {% italic: Puzell %} whom they tearme so pure?

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: A Maid, they say.

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: A Maid? And be so martiall?

lines.speaker: Bur.
lines.text: Pray God she proue not masculine ere long:

lines.speaker: Bur.
lines.text: If vnderneath the Standard of the French

lines.speaker: Bur.
lines.text: She carry Armour, as she hath begun.

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: Well, let them practise and conuerse with spirits.

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: God is our Fortresse, in whose conquering name

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: Let vs resolue to scale their flinty bulwarkes.

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Ascend braue {% italic: Talbot %}, we will follow thee.

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: Not altogether: Better farre I guesse,

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: That we do make our entrance seuerall wayes:

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: That if it chance the one of vs do faile,

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: The other yet may rise against their force.

lines.speaker: Bed.
lines.text: Agreed; Ile to yond corner.

lines.speaker: Bur.
lines.text: And I to this.

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: And heere will {% italic: Talbot %} mount, or make his graue.

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: Now {% italic: Salisbury %}, for thee and for the right

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: Of English {% italic: Henry %}, shall this night appeare

lines.speaker: Tal.
lines.text: How much in duty, I am bound to both.

lines.speaker: Sent.
lines.text: Arme, arme, the enemy doth make assault.

lines.speaker: Alan.
lines.text: How now my Lords? what all vnreadie so?

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: Vnready? I am glad we scap'd so well.

lines.speaker: Reig.
lines.text: 'Twas time (I trow) to wake and leaue our beds,

lines.speaker: Reig.
lines.text: Hearing Alarums at our Chamber doores.

lines.speaker: Alan.
lines.text: Of all exploits since first I follow'd Armes,

lines.speaker: Alan.
lines.text: Nere heard I of a warlike enterprize

lines.speaker: Alan.
lines.text: More venturous, or desperate then this.

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: I thinke this {% italic: Talbot %} be a Fiend of Hell.

lines.speaker: Reig.
lines.text: If not of Hell, the Heauens sure fauour him.

lines.speaker: Alans.
lines.text: Here Commeth {% italic: Charles %}, I maruell how he sped?

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: Tut, holy {% italic: Ioane %} was his defensiue Guard.

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: Is this thy cunning, thou deceitfull Dame?

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: Didst thou at first to flatter vs withall,

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: Make vs partakers of a little gayne,

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: That now our losse might be ten times so much?

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: Wherefore is {% italic: Charles %} impatient with his friend?

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: At all times will you haue my Power alike?

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: Sleeping or waking, must I still preuayle,

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: Or will you blame and lay the fault on me?

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: Improuident Souldiors, had your Watch been good,

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: This sudden Mischiefe neuer could haue falne.

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: Duke of Alanson, this was your default,

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: That being Captaine of the Watch to Night,

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: Did looke no better to that weightie Charge.

lines.speaker: Alans.
lines.text: Had all your Quarters been as safely kept,

lines.speaker: Alans.
lines.text: As that whereof I had the gouernment,

lines.speaker: Alans.
lines.text: We had not beene thus shamefully surpriz'd.

lines.speaker: Bast.
lines.text: Mine was secure.

lines.speaker: Reig.
lines.text: And so was mine, my Lord.

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: And for my selfe, most part of all this Night

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: Within her Quarter, and mine owne Precinct,

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: I was imploy'd in passing to and fro,

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: About relieuing of the Centinels.

lines.speaker: Charl.
lines.text: Then how, or which way, should they first breake in?

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: Question (my Lords) no further of the case,

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: How or which way; 'tis sure they found some place,

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: But weakely guarded, where the breach was made:

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: And now there, rests no other shift but this,

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: To gather our Souldiors, scatter'd and disperc't,

lines.speaker: Ioane.
lines.text: And lay new Plat‑formes to endammage them.

lines.speaker: Sould.
lines.text: Ile be so bold to take what they haue left:

lines.speaker: Sould.
lines.text: The Cry of {% italic: Talbot %} serues me for a Sword,

lines.speaker: Sould.
lines.text: For I haue loaden me with many Spoyles,

lines.speaker: Sould.
lines.text: Vsing no other Weapon but his Name.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: The Day begins to breake, and Night is fled,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Whose pitchy Mantle ouer‑vayl'd the Earth.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Here sound Retreat, and cease our hot pursuit.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Bring forth the Body of old {% italic: Salisbury %},

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: And here aduance it in the Market‑Place,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: The middle Centure of this cursed Towne.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Now haue I pay'd my Vow vnto his Soule:

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: For euery drop of blood was drawne from him,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: There hath at least fiue Frenchmen dyed to night.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: And that hereafter Ages may behold

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: What ruine happened in reuenge of him,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Within their chiefest Temple Ile erect

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: A Tombe, wherein his Corps shall be interr'd:

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Vpon the which, that euery one may reade,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Shall be engrau'd the sacke of Orleance,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: The trecherous manner of his mournefull death,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: And what a terror he had beene to France.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: But Lords, in all our bloudy Massacre,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: I muse we met not with the Dolphins Grace,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: His new‑come Champion, vertuous {% italic: Ioane %} of Acre,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Nor any of his false Confederates.

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: 'Tis thought Lord {% italic: Talbot %}, when the fight began,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Rows'd on the sudden from their drowsie Beds,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: They did amongst the troupes of armed men,

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Leape o're the Walls for refuge in the field.

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: My selfe, as farre as I could well discerne,

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: For smoake, and duskie vapours of the night,

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: Am sure I scar'd the Dolphin and his Trull,

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: When Arme in Arme they both came swiftly running,

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: Like to a payre of louing Turtle‑Doues,

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: That could not liue asunder day or night.

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: After that things are set in order here,

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: Wee'le follow them with all the power we haue.

lines.speaker: Mess
lines.text: All hayle, my Lords: which of this Princely trayne

lines.speaker: Mess
lines.text: Call ye the Warlike {% italic: Talbot %}, for his Acts

lines.speaker: Mess
lines.text: So much applauded through the Realme of France ?

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Here is the {% italic: Talbot %}, who would speak with him ?

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: The vertuous Lady, Countesse of Ouergne,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: With modestie admiring thy Renowne,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: By me entreats (great Lord) thou would'st vouchsafe

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: To visit her poore Castle where she lyes,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: That she may boast she hath beheld the man,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Whose glory fills the World with lowd report.

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: Is it euen so? Nay, then I see our Warres

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: Will turne vnto a peacefull Comick sport,

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: When Ladyes craue to be encountred with.

lines.speaker: Burg.
lines.text: You may not (my Lord) despise her gentle suit.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Ne're trust me then: for when a World of men

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Could not preuayle with all their Oratorie,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Yec hath a Womans kindnesse ouer‑rul'd:

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: And therefore tell her, I returne great thankes,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: And in submission will attend on her.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Will not your Honors beare me company?

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: No, truly, 'tis more then manners will:

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: And I haue heard it sayd, Vnbidden Guests

lines.speaker: Bedf.
lines.text: Are often welcommest when they are gone.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Well then, alone (since there's no remedie)

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: I meane to proue this Ladyes courtesie.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Come hither Captaine, you perceiue my minde.

lines.speaker: Capt.
lines.text: I doe my Lord, and meane accordingly.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Porter, remember what I gaue in charge,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: And when you haue done so, bring the Keyes to me.

lines.speaker: Port.
lines.text: Madame, I will.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: The Plot is layd, if all things fall out right,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: I shall as famous be by this exploit,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: As Scythian {% italic: Tomyris %} by {% italic: Cyrus %} death.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Great is the rumour of this dreadfull Knight,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: And his atchieuements of no lesse account:

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Faine would mine eyes be witnesse with mine eares,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: To giue their censure of these rare reports.

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Madame, according as your Ladyship desir'd,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: By Message crau'd, so is Lord {% italic: Talbot %} come.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: And he is welcome: what? is this the man?

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Madame, it is.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Is this the Scourge of France?

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Is this the {% italic: Talbot %}, so much fear'd abroad?

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: That with his Name the Mothers still their Babes?

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: I see Report is fabulous and false.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: I thought I should haue seene some {% italic: Hercules %},

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: A second {% italic: Hector %}, for his grim aspect,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: And large proportion of his strong knit Limbes,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Alas, this is a Child, a silly Dwarfe:

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: It cannot be, this weake and writhled shrimpe

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Should strike such terror to his Enemies.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Madame, I haue beene bold to trouble you:

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: But since your Ladyship is not at leysure,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Ile sort some other time to visit you.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: What meanes he now?

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Goe aske him, whither he goes?

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: Stay my Lord {% italic: Talbot %}, for my Lady craues,

lines.speaker: Mess.
lines.text: To know the cause of your abrupt departure?

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Marry, for that shee's in a wrong beleefe,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: I goe to certifie her {% italic: Talbot's %} here.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: If thou be he, then art thou Prisoner.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Prisoner? to whom?

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: To me, blood‑thirstie Lord:

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: And for that cause I trayn'd thee to my House.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Long time thy shadow hath been thrall to me,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: For in my Gallery thy Picture hangs:

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: But now the substance shall endure the like,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: And I will chayne these Legges and Armes of thine,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: That hast by Tyrannie these many yeeres

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Wasted our Countrey, slaine our Citizens,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: And sent our Sonnes and Husbands captiuate.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Ha, ha, ha.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Laughest thou Wretch?

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Thy mirth shall turne to moane.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: I laugh to see your Ladyship so fond,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: To thinke, that you haue ought but {% italic: Talbots %} shadow,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Whereon to practise your seueritie.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Why? art not thou the man?

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: I am indeede.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: Then haue I substance too.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: No, no, I am but shadow of my selfe:

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: You are deceiu'd, my substance is not here;

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: For what you see, is but the smallest part,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: And least proportion of Humanitie:

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: I tell you Madame, were the whole Frame here,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: It is of such a spacious loftie pitch,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: Your Roofe were not sufficient to contayn't.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: This is a Riddling Merchant for the nonce,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: He will be here, and yet he is not here:

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: How can these contrarieties agree?

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: That will I shew you presently.

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: How say you Madame? are you now perswaded,

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: That {% italic: Talbot %} is but shadow of himselfe?

lines.speaker: Talb.
lines.text: These are his substance, sinewes, armes, and strength,

lines.text: With which he yoaketh your rebellious Neckes,

lines.text: Let my presumption not prouoke thy wrath,

lines.text: For I am sorry, that with reuerence

lines.text: Be not dismay'd, faire Lady, nor misconster

lines.text: The minde of {% italic: Talbot %}, as you did mistake

lines.text: Nor other satisfaction doe I craue,

lines.text: But onely with your patience, that we may

lines.text: For Souldiers stomacks alwayes serue them well.

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: With all my heart, and thinke me honored,

lines.speaker: Count.
lines.text: To feast so great a Warrior in my House.

lines.text: Great Lords and Gentlemen,

lines.text: What meanes this silence?

lines.text: Dare no man answer in a Case of Truth?

lines.text: Within the Temple Hall we were too lowd,

lines.text: The Garden here is more conuenient.

lines.text: Or else was wrangling {% italic: Somerset %} in th'error?

lines.speaker: Suff.
lines.text: And neuer yet could frame my will to it,

lines.text: Iudge you, my Lord of Warwicke, then be­

lines.text: To saue your Subiects from such massacre

lines.speaker: Alan.
lines.text: And ruthlesse slaughters as are dayly seene

lines.speaker: Alan.
lines.text: By our proceeding in Hostility,

lines.text: Onely reseru'd, you claime no interest

lines.text: In any our Townes of Garrison.

lines.text: Then sweare Allegeance to his Maiesty,

lines.speaker: Yor.
lines.text: As thou art Knight, neuer to disobey,

lines.speaker: Yor.
lines.text: Nor be Rebellious to the Crowne of England,

lines.speaker: Yor.
lines.text: Thou nor thy Nobles, to the Crowne of England.

lines.speaker: Yor.
lines.text: So, now dismisse your Army when ye please:

lines.speaker: Yor.
lines.text: Hang vp your Ensignes, let your Drummes be still,

lines.speaker: Yor.
lines.text: For heere we entertaine a solemne peace.

lines.text: Of beauteous {% italic: Margaret %} hath astonish'd me:

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: Her vertues graced with externall gifts,

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: Do breed Loues setled passions in my heart,

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: And like as rigour of tempestuous gustes

lines.text: Either to suffer Shipwracke, or arriue

lines.text: But with as humble lowlinesse of minde,

lines.text: She is content to be at your command:

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: Command I meane, of Vertuous chaste intents,

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: To Loue, and Honor {% italic: Henry %} as her Lord.

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: That {% italic: Marg'ret %} may be Englands Royall Queene.

lines.text: Vnto another Lady of esteeme,

lines.text: Why what (I pray) is {% italic: Margaret %} more

lines.text: Yes my Lord, her Father is a King,

lines.text: Where {% italic: Reignier %} sooner will receyue, than giue.

lines.text: A Dowre my Lords? Disgrace not so your King,

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: That he should be so abiect, base, and poore,

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: To choose for wealth, and not for perfect Loue.

lines.text: {% italic: Henry %} is able to enrich his Queene,

lines.text: Most of all these reasons bindeth vs,

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: An Age of discord and continuall strife,

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: Whereas the contrarie bringeth blisse,

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: And is a patterne of Celestiall peace.

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: Whom should we match with {% italic: Henry %} being a King,

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: But {% italic: Margaret %}, that is daughter to a King:

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: Her peerelesse feature, ioyned with her birth,

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: Approues her fit for none, but for a King.

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: Her valiant courage, and vndaunted spirit,

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: (More then in women commonly is seene)

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: Will answer our hope in issue of a King.

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: For {% italic: Henry %}, sonne vnto a Conqueror,

lines.speaker: Suf.

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: If with a Lady of so high resolue,

lines.speaker: Suf.
lines.text: (As is faire {% italic: Margaret %}) he be link'd in loue.

lines.text: Then yeeld my Lords, and heere conclude with mee,
